Lorsque vous effectuez une `git commit` dans Git, vous pouvez ajouter l'option `-a` ou `-m` pour spécifier comment vous souhaitez ajouter vos modifications dans le commit.

L'option `-a` (ou `--all`) est utilisée pour inclure automatiquement toutes les modifications de fichiers qui ont été modifiés et suivis par Git. Cela signifie que vous n'avez pas besoin d'ajouter manuellement chaque fichier modifié en utilisant la commande `git add` avant de faire un commit. Cependant, notez que les nouveaux fichiers non suivis ne seront pas inclus dans le commit avec cette option.

L'option `-m` (ou `--message`) est utilisée pour spécifier un message de commit directement en ligne de commande. Vous pouvez utiliser cette option pour fournir une brève description de vos modifications ou pour ajouter des informations supplémentaires sur le commit. Par exemple, vous pouvez utiliser la commande `git commit -m "Correction d'une faute de frappe dans le fichier README.md"` pour effectuer un commit avec un message spécifique.

En résumé, l'option `-a` permet d'inclure automatiquement toutes les modifications suivies dans le commit, tandis que l'option `-m` permet de spécifier un message de commit directement en ligne de commande. Vous pouvez également utiliser ces options ensemble si vous le souhaitez.

## Comparing files 

### How can I tell what I have changed?

Git has a staging area in which it stores files with changes you want to save that haven't been saved yet. Putting files in the staging area is like putting things in a box, while committing those changes is like putting that box in the mail: you can add more things to the box or take things out as often as you want, but once you put it in the mail, you can't make further changes.

Staging Area

`git status` shows you which files are in this staging area, and which files have changes that haven't yet been put there. In order to compare the file as it currently is to what you last saved, you can use `git diff filename`. `git diff` without any filenames will show you all the changes in your repository, while `git diff directory` will show you the changes to the files in some directory.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

You have been put in the dental repository. Use `git diff` to see what changes have been made to the files.

```
git diff
git diff -r HEAD filename -> comparer a staged file with last commited
git diff filename -> compare a unstaged file with last committed version
git diff directory ->
git diff -r HEAD -> compare all staged files with last commited versions
```

# Storing data with Git
Git store data trhough git commit which have 3 parts:
- commit contains the metadata 
- Tree track the names and locations in the repository
- Blob - binary large object, compressed snapshot of a file's contents

`Git log` donnera les commit effectués dans l'ordre chronologique, `q` to exit
`Git Hash`: 
`git show`: + début du hash

## View changes 

`git diff -r HEAD` : compare staged files to the version in the last commit
`git diff -r HEAD~1`: compare with the second most recnet commit 
`git diff ~r HEAD~2`: compare with the commit before that

`git show HEAD~3`: hash, metadata et diff de la 3ème upload
`git diff 3ndoej3 187363g` or `git diff HEAD~2 HEAD~3`: comparer les fichiers entre 2.
`git annotate file`: show line by line diff and author

## Undoing changes before committing 

To unstaged a file:
```
git reset HEAD summary_statistics.csv
nano summary_statistics.csv
git add summary_statistics.csv
git commit -m "Adding age summary statistics"
```

![[Pasted image 20230830191435.png]]

• Suppose we need to undo changes to a file in the repository
`git checkout -- summary_statistics.csv`
• checkout means switching to a different version
	o Defaults to the last commit
• This means losing all changes made to the unstaged file forever

**remove all unstaged files**
```
git reset HEAD
git checkout -- report.md -> revert only report.md
git checkout . -> revert all file to last commit
git add .
git commit -m "Restore repo to previous commit"
```

## Restore and reverting

- restrict the number of commit: `git log - 3` ou `git log -3 report.md`
- restrict by date: `git log --since='Month Day Year'` or `git log --since='Apr 2 2022' --until='Apr 11 2022'`
- from a date: `git log --since 'month day year'`
- Restore an old version of a file: `git checkout -- filename` or `git checkout df9fb34 filename`
- Restore a entierely repo `git checkout dceifn43` and `git checkout HEAD~1`

## Cleaning a repository

`git clean -n` see files are not being tracked
`git clean -f` delete those files

# Configuring Git

**Levels of settings**
• git config --list
• Git has three levels of settings:
1. --local : settings for one specific project
2. --global : settings for all of our projects
3. --system

**Create an alias**
- `git config --global user.email johnsmith@datacamp.com`: change the mail address
- `git config --global alias.ci 'commit -m'` set up an alias.ci (`git ci`)
- git config --global --list: track alias name

**ignore files**
- *.log: ignore some files
